{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657059"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:22:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:22:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19084"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19084"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82649"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11818"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19084"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67789"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3809"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8150"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28253"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82649"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents for discussion of her recent breast cancer diagnosis. Core needle biopsy of a 2.5 cm right breast mass was performed last week. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer immunohistochemistry results reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Oestrogen receptor: negative\u003Cbr /\u003E- Progesterone receptor: negative\u003Cbr /\u003E- HER2: negative\u003Cbr /\u003E- Ki-67: 80%\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following breast cancer subtypes has the poorest overall prognosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oestrogen receptor negative, progesterone receptor negative, HER2 positive","Oestrogen receptor positive, progesterone receptor positive, HER2 negative","Oestrogen receptor negative, progesterone receptor negative, HER2 negative","Oestrogen receptor positive, progesterone receptor positive, HER2 positive","Oestrogen receptor positive, progesterone receptor negative, HER2 positive"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has triple-negative breast cancer (TNBC), characterised by the absence of oestrogen receptors, progesterone receptors, and HER2 expression. The high Ki-67 indicates rapid cell proliferation, which is typical of TNBC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOestrogen receptor negative, progesterone receptor negative, HER2 negative\u003C/strong\u003E breast cancer (triple-negative) generally has the poorest prognosis among breast cancer subtypes. This is primarily because these cancers lack therapeutic targets for hormonal therapy or HER2-directed therapy, leaving chemotherapy as the main treatment option. They tend to be more aggressive and have a greater risk of early recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOestrogen receptor positive, progesterone receptor positive, HER2 negative\u003C/strong\u003E breast cancers typically have a favourable prognosis. These cancers can be treated with endocrine therapy such as tamoxifen or aromatase inhibitors, which are generally well-tolerated and effective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOestrogen receptor positive, progesterone receptor negative, HER2 positive\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eoestrogen receptor negative, progesterone receptor negative, HER2 positive\u003C/strong\u003E cancers historically had poor prognoses, but the development of HER2-targeted therapies (such as trastuzumab) has significantly improved outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOestrogen receptor positive, progesterone receptor positive, HER2 positive\u003C/strong\u003E cancers can be treated with both endocrine therapy and HER2-targeted therapy, often resulting in good outcomes despite being positive for multiple markers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe molecular subtype of breast cancer is crucial for determining treatment approach and predicting prognosis. While HER2-positive breast cancers were historically associated with poor outcomes, the development of targeted therapies has dramatically improved their prognosis. In contrast, triple-negative breast cancers remain challenging to treat due to the lack of targeted therapy options.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Triple negative breast cancer has the poorest prognosis due to limited targeted treatment options.","HER2 positivity was historically associated with poor outcomes, but targeted therapies have significantly improved prognosis.","Hormone receptor status and HER2 status are crucial determinants of breast cancer treatment and prognosis."],"references":["Aysola et al. Triple Negative Breast Cancer \u2013 An Overview. Hereditary Genet. 2014, https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4181680/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67789"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19084"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67789"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T14:12:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T14:12:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11818"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82649"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"cr